\section{Course topics}
The course will cover most of the following topics:
\begin{itemize}
\item Maximum Flow: The Goldberg-Tarjan Push-Relabel max-flow algorithm
\item Minimum cuts: Gomory-Hu tree cuts, global minimum cuts
\item Min-Cost Flow: cancellation of negative cycle, capacity scaling,
  min cycle mean, overview of Goldberg-Tarjan algorithm
\item Matching: Edmonds algorithm for the unweighted case. 
\item Coloring: greedy vertex coloring and edge coloring.
\item Connectivity: Menger's Theorem.
\item Linear Programming: Farkas' Lemma, duality, complementary
  slackness, Simplex algorithm.
\item If time permits, some of these topics: PTAS for fractional
  covering/packing, online covering/packing, separator theorem for
  planar graphs.

\end{itemize}
\section{Course requirements}
This is an advanced course. What does it mean?
\begin{itemize}
\item Not a mass audience course: ``teacher lectures and students hope
  for an easy exam''... I am here to teach, and you are here to improve
  your knowledge and skills in algorithm design and analysis. 
\item Style of presentation is less formal, a lot of intuition (aka
  hand-waiving), but students must be able to fill the details.
\item Small class - everybody gets a chance to participate. Students
  are expected to contribute to the course and should not restrict their
  participation to passive attendance.
\item No assistant - I will be your teaching assistant.
\item Homework questions are challenging - they do not repeat material
  taught in class but require introduction of new ideas. You are
  expected to set aside a few hours each week for thinking about the
  homework.
\item Homework will be solved on the board by the students. You are
  requested to hand solved homework - just to make sure you have a
  strict deadline for trying to deal with the homework. 
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Grading Policy}
\begin{description}
\item To pass the course, you must pass the final exam!
\item[Homework] Students must hand in solutions for
  75\% of the homework questions:
\[
\frac{\text{number of submitted answers}}{\text{sum of questions asked over the semester}} \geq \frac 34.
\]
Handed homework will not be graded. Instead, exercises will solved by
the students during class recitations. Each presented solution that is
correct will grant at least $1$ bonus point to the final grade The
bonus is based be based on the quality of the presented solutions, the
number of presented solutions, and difficulty of question. The
homework grade will not decrease your final grade.
\item[Final Exam] A regular exam will be given.
\end{description}

